As we can see, AssetsNonCurrent has only data since mid of 2018 and prior to that, there was no special entry in the balancesheet. However, per definition AssetsNonCurrent = Assets - AssetsCurrent. So it is actually not necessary to have to column, since it can be calculated easily.

Analyze the whole dataset

Preparation

Sort the dataset by period and set period as index. Since the years from before 2012 are often not "complete", we only want entries starting from 2012.

{% raw %} 
df_analyze_whole = df_cleaned.sort_values('period').set_index('period')
df_analyze_whole = df_analyze_whole.loc[df_analyze_whole.index > pd.to_datetime('01-01-2012')]
df_analyze_whole.shape

(113202, 104)
{% endraw %}

Correlation between earnings in the past and future earnings

As an idea: let us see if there is a relation between the average earning gain from 2012 to 2016 compared to the earning gain from 2016 to 2017.

{% raw %} 
# First, we only consider "yearly" reports: 10-K.
yearly_earnings = df_analyze_whole[df_analyze_whole.form == "10-K"]
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
# we are only interested in the ticker, cik and Earnings columns. the period is in the index
yearly_earnings = yearly_earnings[['ticker', 'cik','RetainedEarningsAccumulatedDeficit']]

# extracting the year from the index as a column
yearly_earnings['year'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(yearly_earnings.index).year
# creating a cik_ticker columnt that combines the cik and the ticker, simply for convenience
yearly_earnings['cik_ticker'] = yearly_earnings['cik'].map(str) + '-' + yearly_earnings['ticker']
{% endraw %}

It could happen that for some special reason there is more than one yearly report during a year. We cannot keep thes entries, since pivoting the table will not be possible anymore. The following lines remove such companies from the dataset.

{% raw %} 
# we create a crosstab between cik and year, normally every cell should contain a 1. Therfore we select the ones "> 1".
# This produces a TRUE / FALSE Matrix witth cik and year. Then we sum rowwise.
counts = (pd.crosstab(yearly_earnings.cik, yearly_earnings.year)>1).sum(axis=1)

# the indexes of rows in the counts table with counts > 0 are the ciks with multiple entries in at least one year and have to be removed
multiple_entries = counts[counts > 0].index.tolist()

# removing the entries
yearly_earnings = yearly_earnings[~yearly_earnings['cik'].isin(multiple_entries)]
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
# setting the "cik" as index column
yearly_eanrings_indexed = yearly_earnings.set_index('cik')

# next we can pivot the data. we want to hove a column for every year and every cik should have its own row
earnings_per_year = yearly_eanrings_indexed.pivot(index="cik_ticker", columns='year', values = 'RetainedEarningsAccumulatedDeficit')

# we wanna calculate the average "earnings"-gain between 2012 and 2016, as well as between 2016 and 2017, so we just need these columns
ernings_per_year_selected = earnings_per_year[[2012,2016,2017]]

# we removing entries with uncomplete date
ernings_per_year_selected = ernings_per_year_selected.dropna()
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
# calculating the "earning" gain
ernings_per_year_selected['12-16'] = ((ernings_per_year_selected[2016] / ernings_per_year_selected[2012]) - 1) / 5
ernings_per_year_selected['16-17'] = (ernings_per_year_selected[2017] /  ernings_per_year_selected[2016]) - 1
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15,7))
sns.scatterplot(data = ernings_per_year_selected, x = '12-16', y = '16-17',  ax=ax)
ax.set_xlim(-5,5)
ax.set_ylim(-5,5)
plt.show()
